Subject:    "that turns out not to be the case"
From:       <a href="?a=95837693600014&r=1&w=2">Rob Austein &lt;SRA () MIT-XX ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198511">1985-11-13 0:17:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426622&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426622&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Actually, the NIC has already begun delegating IN-ADDR.ARPA.
18.IN-ADDR.ARPA has already been delegated to MIT.  Anybody who has a
LAN or two should check to see just where their net has been
delegated; in an absence of any real data the NIC has come up with
some really interesting delegations.  I was amused to find MIT-AI-NET
delegated to a LSI-11 gateway.

As for usefulness, IN-ADDR is basicly the only reliable way to do the
number to name translation.  Paul's TOPS-20 resolver code (which I am
beta-testing) uses IN-ADDR, not inverse queries, with good reason.
After you have gone to all the work of a tree traversal to do an
inverse query, you still don't have a definite answer if it fails.
Pretty useless.  XX is already putting out occasional IN-ADDR queries,
and I doubt it is unique in that respect.

--Rob

